<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Transport Select Committee</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Arial Bold'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Arial Bold'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence from the</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Bold'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Department for Transport</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Bold'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> (LTD0019)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government believes that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> communities are better placed than Central Government to make decisions that affect their local areas. Local Authorities have long argued for a more devolved approach for local major schemes, which is why the Go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vernment has taken this forward.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> believes that the new system it is putting into place for local major transport schemes will help schemes which have impacts beyond the boundaries of individual local transport authorities be considered at that the level of those impacts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at cross bound</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ary level</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 24.72pt; padding-left:3.63pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government believes that there are already a number of mechanisms available to promoting authorities to access private and other alternative methods of funding. However it will continue to work with the sector to see if more can be done.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> decision-making on transport expenditure? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What impact will the devolution </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">in 2015 of funding to Local Transport Bodies and the introduction of the Single Local Growth Fund have?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Verdana; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local Transport policy sits within the Government’s overall policy of greate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r localism; the belief that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> communities are better placed than Central Government to make decisions that affect their local areas. Local Authorities have long argued for a more devolved approach for local major schemes, which is why the Go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vernment has taken this forward.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> majo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r transport schemes (i.e. those costing over £5m) are not readily affordable for most local authorities, and so have traditionally been funded by central Government as individual projects through various bidding processes, unlike the other main local trans</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">port funding streams which are distributed by formula such as the Integrated Transport Block a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd Highway Maintenance budgets.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Coalition Government wished to create a genuinely devolved system, but it was recognised that a transitional period would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">required, due the number of schemes already in development and the time it would take to develop new ones.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In October 2010 therefore, the Government initiated a competitive process, to rationalise the existing pipeline of major schemes for which local aut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">horities already had (or had bid for) early </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stage approval from Government. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In January 2012 the Government consul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ted on a proposal to introduce </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more devolved system from 2015 and various options were considered.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There was near-universal approval for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the principle for devolution of this funding and broad support for the G</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">overnment’s key proposals that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Funding should be devolved on a simple per-capita basis to new Local Transport Bodies (LTBs) which would operat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at broadly the same geography as Local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) and would include Local Authorities and LEPs as members.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The existing fr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ameworks for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">scheme assessment:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The Transport Business Case and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">WebTAG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should continue to be used.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Assurance Frameworks would be required for LTBs with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">minimum standards of governance, financial management, accountability and meeting and testing value for money.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The key element in the proposed system was the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">establishment of Local Transport B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">odies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which would receive and make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decisions on the devolved f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unding.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department decided against devolving direct to Local Authority level as the funds would be spread too thinly to be able to fund all but the smallest major schemes. Therefore, while the individual Local Authorities would be the scheme delivery b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">odies as before, the LTB would replace </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as the scheme funder.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LTBs were not to be permanent staffed organisations but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">voluntary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">groupings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of Local Authorities and Local Enterprise Partnerships and possibly others. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It was proposed that these bodies </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">should be based broadly on existing LEP geography</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Membership of the LTB was for local decision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, provided that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">all Local Transport Authorities and the LEPs in the relevant area </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">had</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a right of LTB membership, but that democratically elected bodies should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">form a voting majority on LTBs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some respondents to the consultation argued that assurance frameworks for LTBs were unnecessary and that existing local authority decision making arrangements would suffice. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> thought that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assurance framework approach was necessary because LTBs were new bodies making decisions on funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Local Authorities and because some requirements, particularly on value for money,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> were specific to major schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and unlikely to be covered by exist</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing local authority protocols.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department then invited prospective LTBs to develop assurance frameworks and published guidance setting out the minimum requirem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ents that would need to be met.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> invited LTBs to start drawing up their scheme prioritie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s and provided all LTBs with an indicative funding guideline in January 2013.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In October 2012, Lord Heseltine’s ‘No Stone Unturned’ report recommended the pooling and devolution of various funding streams across Government. That recommendation was accepte</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d in principle by Government in March 2013 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and the Spending Round announcement in June 2013 confirmed local authority major schemes as one of the funding streams that would make up the Local Growth Fund.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This meant that, while LTBs would, in the immediate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> future, continue to prioritise and develop schemes as had been planned, the funding from 2015 would be devolved in a different way than had been envisaged</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> up to that point</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Namely:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Instead of being allocated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">solely </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by formula </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a large proportion of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Local Growth Fund allocations would be competitive, on the basis of Strategic Economic Plans submitted to Government.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a more distinct policy focus of economic growth for the Local Growth Fund</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decision makers for the devolved funds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> would be Lo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cal Enterprise Partnerships as opposed to LTBs, although LTBs may continue to have a role, depending on local arrangements.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The competitive nature of the funding, and the inclusion of other funding streams provides</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> areas with the opportunity, if they are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">successful, to fund much larger schemes than would have been possible. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do local bodies (including local authorities, local enterprise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport authorities and local transport boards) have the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">capacity to assess, prioritise and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">deliver local transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look like?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the new arrangements, it would remain the responsibility of the promoting local authority (whether a local transport authority, Integrat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed Transport Authority, Combined Authority or any other joint body) to develop the initial business case for the scheme, apply for any statutory consents required, and design and deliver the scheme, as has always been the case</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What will change is that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the funding will come to the scheme promoter not directly from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but from the LEP from within its Local Growth Fund</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> allocation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The LEP will therefore be in the role of funder and will assume the responsibility that previously sat with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for checki</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">usiness cases submitted by l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthority promoters and ap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proving the release of funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to individual schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LEPs should be able to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">draw upon the expertise within local t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uthorities in order to perform this function. In addition, the Departme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contributed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a total of £5m divided equally between LEPs (except </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) as one-off </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ment for their contribution to t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ransport issues, including their participation in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LTBs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To assist them further the Department is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">making resources available includ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing information for local decision makers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">how to conduct </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">value for money </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assessments.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the best </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q4 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">bodies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> work with each other and with Government departments and national transport agencies?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the past very few schemes have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> physically</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> crossed boundaries and we would expect this to continue to be the case. Where it has happened a single authority has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">had responsibility for the delivery of the scheme but has worked with its neighbour</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(s)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where necessary.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Much more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">common has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where the impacts </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of a scheme go beyond a single</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> authority’s boundaries. In these instances, again the onus has been on the d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elivering authority to lead discussions with neighbouring authorities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Department believes that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he introduction of LTBs and LEPs into the system should</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, given their geographic scope,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> help facilitate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> these discussions as well as help to consider the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">scheme within the context of the (LEP’s) functional economic geography and hence the scheme’s impacts beyond the local authority’s boundaries.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> its guidance on the establishment of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> LTBs, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Department </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">set out that LTBs were free to invite Executive Agencies, such as the Highways Agency, or other relevant bodies, such as Network Rail, to be ‘observer’ (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> non-voting) members of LTBs. This was to help encourage early involvement of those organisations in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LTBs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">consideration of schemes and facilitate better working between them all. Some LTBs have taken up this opportunity.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some schemes are likely to have cross LEP boundary impacts. The Government has consistently encouraged LEPs to look beyond their own bo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">undaries and consider working with their neighbours.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Do the current funding streams for major local transport schemes meet the needs of local authorities? How do current funding streams compare with previous arrangements?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Local Authority Major Schemes programme delivers capital grant funding to schemes in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (excluding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) with a total cost in excess of £5m. It covers a range of schemes both in terms of size and mode (roads, public transport, trams, town centre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> packages, rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">etc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">).  Schemes are promoted, delivered and operated by local transport authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Prior to 2010 the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Regional Fu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nding Allocation (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">RFA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was based around advice from the regions to government regarding regional transport priorities and how available money should be spent. 10-year programmes were consulted upon before Ministers approved them. Whilst this was an attempt at a devolved system i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t put influence in the hands of indirectly elected Regional Assemblies and unelected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Regional Development Agencies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given the wider fiscal position in 2010 and recognising that setting up a truly decentralised system of decision-making for local major tra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nsport schemes would take some time, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a competitive process was set up </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">following the Spending Review 2010 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to decide which LA major schemes should be funded.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a transitional arrangement allowing the Department to create an affordable programme of sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emes selected from those prioritised in the previous Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(RFA) process.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Only those schemes wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere the D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">epartment had already granted initial approval or where a bid document had been submitted to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">epartment were considered further.  Local auth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">orities were challenged to reduce the amount of central Government funding required. This was achieved in part by reducing the scope of the scheme; and also by local authorities and their private sector partners (where possible) contributing more funding. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This led to over £0.7bn being levered in – largely from local authority resources but with some additi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onal private developer funding.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The process</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consisted of three main stages:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Supported Pool - final decisions taken in February 2011 to fund 10 schemes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hich had high value for money</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Pre-qualification Pool - initial decisions taken in February 2011 to continue to consider a sub-set of the remaining schemes based on the quality of the bids made by the scheme promoters </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on the extent to which scheme promo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ters reduced the overall </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> contribution.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Development Pool - final decisions taken in late 2011/2012 on which of the approved Pre-Qualification schemes and the remaining eligible schemes should be funded based on the quality of their bids.</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As a result of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> these decisions, a programme of 60 schemes was prioritised by the Coalition Government for funding. The current status of those schemes is:</span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">56 schemes have been provisionally approved for funding, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are now complete;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">0</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of these have been fully approval and are now under construction;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are at various stages of development with outstanding statutory and/or procurement approvals to complete;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the remaining 4 schemes in the programme: 2 were rejected; 1 has been incorpo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rated into the Sheffield-Rotherham tram-train scheme; and 1 (Isles of Scilly Link) is still in development.</span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A list showing the current status of the programme approved by the Coalition Government is at Annex A.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q7 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How can local authorities attract great</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">er investment from the private sector for the delivery and maintenance of local transport infrastructure? What scope is there for the use of alternative funding streams?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are a number of methods which local authorities can use to lever in greater inv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">estment from the private sector for the delivery of local highways maintenance and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">other transport infrastructure.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Developer contributio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ns (or Section 106) have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> been widely used for many years to fund transport infrastructure that is necessary for new dev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elopment to go ahead. The Community Infrastructure Levy (CIL) also provides similar opportunities to capture private sector financial contributions for investment in local transport infrastructure. Many small to medium scale transport projects such as thos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e that are tackling bottlenecks on the local highway network are funded in full or part by such funding contributi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ons.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Prudential borrowing has also been available to local authorities for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">years. There are examples of local authorities which using prudential borrowing as means of investing in the maintenance of their highways. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Blackpool</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, for example, has implemented a project known as Project 30 to revitalise its road network and bring about</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> savings of over £100m over 25 years.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Similarly the UK Guarantee has been used by the Mayor of London to borrow £1bn at a preferential rate to support the extension of London Underground's Northern Line into Battersea as part of the Nine Elms regeneration</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Value capture mechanisms are available for local authorities to use a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> way of leveraging private investment to cover all or part of the cost of infrastructure improvements. Whilst relatively common in North America, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> version Tax Increment Financ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e (TIF) has not yet been as widely used. TIF seeks to capture local public sector revenues (e.g. non-domestic rates) that would not have arisen without public sector infrastructure investment. A local authority could then use the income to repay the cost o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f the transport infrastructure. Such a mechanism is likely to be appropriate where transport infrastructure is required to support development or regeneration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In December 2012 the Government published its revised approach to PFI: the new model is called </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">PF2 (Private Finance 2). The aim is for PF2 projects to work in a similar way to the previous PFI system in that they will be commissioned by the public sector from a predominantly private sector body through a long-term contract, generally covering the de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sign, construction and maintenance of infrastructure, paid for over the life of the contract.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The new PF2 approach varies from the previous PFI model by providing for: a government minority equity stake in projects; accelerated delivery (maximum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">procurement time 18 months); more flexible service provision (removing soft services); greater transparency; more appropriate risk allocation (e.g. hand back conditions, maintenance profiles); and wider sources of finance.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> PFI projects tended to be large </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">scale and were assessed for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">VfM</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and approved by both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and HMT – PF2 assessment will continue to follow the principles set out in The Green Book as was the case with PFI.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Q8 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">How clear are the lines of accountability for local decision making on transpo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">rt expenditure?</span><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are various levels of decision making on the Local Growth Fund. These will apply to transport and non-transport elements.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Firstly the LEP will decide on the content of the Strategic Economic Plans to be submitted to Government in M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arch 2014 and the projects that are named within them. We expect those plans to be agreed by consensus among LEP partners, including the local authorities.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">When Growth Deals are agreed in July 2014 ministers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will, as part of that process, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decide on the al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">location of Local Growth Fund money to each LEPs based on the quality of the plans received.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the same time Ministers will decide on the degree of autonomy to give to each LEP to make changes to the composition of their plan and the projects to be funde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It will be essential to ensure that proper accountability is in place for the Local Growth Fund to ensure regularity, propriety and value for money. There are a range of possible mechanisms to achieve this and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he Government is still considering the mo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">st appropriate approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">LEPs may choose to adopt the existing LTB frameworks for their own purposes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> while some may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">select </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a different model</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We will want to strike a balance between having proper safeguards in place while ensuring that LEPs are not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hampered by an over-prescriptive approach.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Accountability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> arrangements for other transport funding streams provided by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to local authorities are set out in detail in the Department’s Accountability System Statement.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Annex A - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">l Authority Major Sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">heme Status</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">of 1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">December 2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt; width:486pt"><tr><td colspan="2" style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:486pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Local Authority Major Scheme Status </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(as at 13</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> December 2013)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">*Note these are all the schemes on which this Government has taken a decision. It does not include those schemes already under construction at the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">election, 23 of the 27 of which are complete.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:249pt"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Complete (6)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">(Nov 12)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">  East of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Exeter</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">(Mar 13)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Mansfield</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Interchange</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">May 13</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">) A164 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Humber</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Bridge</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> to Beverley</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">       “       </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">White Rose Way</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Improvement Scheme </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">(Jul 13)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">   </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Walton</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">Bridge</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'